<h2>Container Padding</h2>
<p>The <b>w3-container</b> class has a default <strong>16px</strong> left and right padding,
    and no top or bottom padding:</p>
<div class="w3-container w3-blue">
    I have no top or bottom padding</div>
<div class="w3-example">
    <h3>Example</h3>
    <div class="w3-code notranslate htmlHigh">
        <span class="tagnamecolor" style="color:brown"><span class="tagcolor" style="color:mediumblue">&lt;</span>div<span class="attributecolor" style="color:red"> class<span class="attributevaluecolor" style="color:mediumblue">="w3-container w3-blue"</span></span><span class="tagcolor" style="color:mediumblue">&gt;</span></span><br>
        I have no top or bottom padding.<br>
        <span class="tagnamecolor" style="color:brown"><span class="tagcolor" style="color:mediumblue">&lt;</span>/div<span class="tagcolor" style="color:mediumblue">&gt;</span></span>
    </div>
    <a class="w3-btn w3-green w3-margin-bottom" href="https://www.w3schools.com/w3css/tryit.asp?filename=tryw3css_containers_padding_default" target="_blank">Try It Yourself »</a>
</div>
<p>Normally you will not have to change the default padding of a container, because paragraphs and heading provide margins that will simulate padding.</p>
<div class="w3-container w3-blue">
    <h1>I am a Heading</h1>
    <p>I am a paragraph.</p>
</div>
